static-xvfb: XKB env overrides + direct-exec xkbcomp (no /bin/sh)

What: patches xkb/ddxLoad.c (the only file in this xserver tree that builds
and runs the xkbcomp command line — verified in Task 3's source inventory,
see patches/README.md) to add two things:

  1. STATIC_XVFB_XKB_BINDIR / STATIC_XVFB_XKM_OUTPUT_DIR env var overrides for the
     xkbcomp binary directory and the compiled-.xkm output directory.
     Neither has ANY existing runtime knob upstream (verified against the
     pinned xorg-server 21.1.20 source: xkb/xkbInit.c's
     XkbProcessArguments only recognizes -xkbdir, which sets
     XkbBaseDirectory — the *data* tree, not the bin dir; XKM_OUTPUT_DIR is
     a build-time-only AC_DEFINE_DIR constant with no getenv() anywhere in
     the tree). Both are compiled-in-default-if-unset, matching the -xkbdir
     flag's own "override only if you ask" shape.

  2. Direct fork()+execv() of xkbcomp instead of Popen()->
     execl("/bin/sh","sh","-c",cmd) (os/utils.c:1425-1512, the ONLY call
     site of which in this whole tree is this file's RunXkbComp — verified
     via `grep -rln 'Popen(\|Pclose('`). A shell-less distroless host has
     no /bin/sh for Popen to exec, so without this the server can never
     compile a keymap and never finishes activating the keyboard on such a
     host — the static-xvfb's explicit boot bar (S2 spike gate).

Why here, why this shape: xkb/ddxLoad.c is the single file that owns both
gaps, so the whole patch is contained to one file. The WIN32 branch (never
built by this pack — pkgsStatic targets Linux only) is left running through
its original Popen-free fopen()+System(buf) path, now written out in a
dedicated #ifdef WIN32 branch instead of sharing an unconditional buf/argv
build with the POSIX path, since the two now diverge (a quoted shell string
for System() vs. an unquoted argv[] for execv()).

Scope check against the S2 trip-wire (~150 lines / many hours): this diff
is ~180 added / ~25 removed lines in one file, one function pair. It is
larger than the ~150-line guidance — flagged explicitly in
patches/README.md and the Task 3 report — but is a single,
well-understood, bounded change (confirmed by a real build + boot, not
guesswork), not an open-ended grind, so it proceeds rather than blocking.

